    <!-- Modal: Malware Classification -->
    <div class="project-modal" id="modal-malware">
        <button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close"><i class="fas fa-xmark"></i></button>
        <div class="modal-banner">
            <img src="./img-malware.jpg" alt="Malware classification pipeline diagram">
        </div>
        <div class="modal-body">
            <span class="modal-tag">Semester Project — Cybersecurity & AI</span>
            <h2>Windows Malware Classification via Graph Analysis (CFG)</h2>
            <div class="modal-meta">
                <span><i class="far fa-calendar"></i> Jan 2026 — Jun 2026</span>
                <span><i class="fas fa-school"></i> EURECOM</span>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Context & Challenge</h3>
                <p>Traditional malware detection uses signature-based methods. These are easily bypassed via code obfuscation. This project aimed to build an <strong>obfuscation-resistant classification method</strong>. We analyzed structural properties of malicious binaries instead of raw content.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Approach</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Binary Analysis:</strong> Extracted Control Flow Graphs (CFG) from 3,850 Windows PE malware samples using the <em>angr</em> framework.</li>
                    <li><strong>Graph Representation:</strong> Converted each CFG into a Machine Learning data structure. We preserved structural relations between code blocks.</li>
                    <li><strong>GNN Classification:</strong> Trained a Graph Isomorphism Network (GIN) using PyTorch Geometric. We classified malware families using only their control graph structure.</li>
                    <li><strong>Optimization:</strong> Used Python multiprocessing to speed up the binary analysis step.</li>
                </ol>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Key Results</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Data Processing:</strong> Extracted 3,850 static CFGs across <strong>235 malware families</strong>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Model Architecture:</strong> Designed a 2-layer GIN with Batch Normalization and Global Mean Pooling. It handles massive graphs without gradient explosion.</li>
                    <li><strong>Performance:</strong> Reached <strong>40.39%</strong> test accuracy on a highly complex 235-class task. Training loss successfully dropped from 5.32 to 3.15.</li>
                    <li><strong>Resilience:</strong> Proved that the GIN model preserves structural density well. It captures obfuscated malware structures better than standard GCNs.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Technologies</h3>
                <div class="modal-tech">
                    <span>Python</span><span>PyTorch Geometric</span><span>angr</span><span>Reverse Engineering</span><span>GNN / GIN</span><span>Multiprocessing</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Modal: SwipeFund -->
    <div class="project-modal" id="modal-swipefund">
        <button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close"><i class="fas fa-xmark"></i></button>
        <div class="modal-banner">
            <img src="./img-swipefund.png" alt="SwipeFund Web App Homepage">
        </div>
        <div class="modal-body">
            <span class="modal-tag">Web Architecture Project</span>
            <h2>SwipeFund — Web App Platform</h2>
            <div class="modal-meta">
                <span><i class="far fa-calendar"></i> Mar 2026 — Jun 2026</span>
                <span><i class="fas fa-school"></i> EURECOM</span>
                <a href="https://charlysejobe.github.io/swipe-fund-web-app/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--accent)"><i class="fas fa-globe"></i> Live Demo</a>
                <a href="https://github.com/charlysejobe/swipe-fund-web-app" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--accent)"><i class="fab fa-github"></i> GitHub</a>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Context & Challenge</h3>
                <p>This was an intensive front-end challenge. Our <strong>4-person team</strong> had only a few weeks to build a full web app from scratch. We chose <strong>vanilla technologies</strong> (HTML5, CSS3, Vanilla JS) instead of modern frameworks. We wanted to deeply understand core web concepts.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Project Scope (Teamwork)</h3>
                <p>We divided the architecture into distinct modules. The app includes:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Interactive map:</strong> Leaflet API integration to show geolocated data with custom markers.</li>
                    <li><strong>State Management:</strong> Custom local system using LocalStorage to keep user sessions active.</li>
                    <li><strong>Accessibility & Quality:</strong> Strict adherence to WCAG accessibility guidelines, W3C validation, and Git version control.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>My Specific Contributions</h3>
                <p>I was in charge of the search features, user interfaces, and final documentation:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Advanced search and filters:</strong> Built the main search engine. Implemented dynamic tags and multi-criteria filters in Vanilla JS.</li>
                    <li><strong>User Interfaces:</strong> Developed the "Profile" and "My Projects" pages from scratch. Focused on DOM manipulation and responsive design.</li>
                    <li><strong>Technical Documentation:</strong> Wrote the final technical report. I detailed our architecture, Gitlab commits, accessibility audits, and carbon footprint estimates.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Takeaways</h3>
                <p>Building a full app without frameworks taught me to <strong>code efficiently under pressure</strong>. It also proved my ability to divide complex tasks, integrate my code with teammates, and document our engineering work clearly.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="modal-section">
                <h3>Technologies</h3>
                <div class="modal-tech">
                    <span>HTML5</span><span>CSS3</span><span>Vanilla JavaScript</span><span>Leaflet API</span><span>LocalStorage</span><span>GitLab</span><span>WCAG</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Modal: IoT -->
    <div class="project-modal" id="modal-iot">
        <button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close"><i class="fas fa-xmark"></i></button>
